er Kelten in der antiken Literatur: ein kurzer Baedeker -- t4. Die antike Mittelmeerwelt und der Alte Orient -- tDie Reise zu den Inseln der Seligen von Hesiod bis Lukian -- tMärchenhexe oder göttliche Ritualexpertin? Kirke und Kult im Kontext der homerischen Nekyia -- tCalypso and the Underworld: The Limits of Comparison -- tWege der Lebenden ins ‚Land ohne Wiederkehr‘ in Mythen und Ritualen der mesopotamischen Antike -- t5. Finno-ugrische Perspektiven -- t“Hard it is to stir my tongue”: Raiding the Otherworld for Poetic Inspiration -- tuupui kolmea sanoa (‚es fehlten ihm drei Zauberworte‘) – Die Jenseitsreisen der Kalevala-Helden -- tPractice-Bound Variation in Cosmology? A Case Study of Movement between Worlds in Finno-Karelian Traditions -- tRegister -- tNamen und Begriffe -- tWissenschaftliche Autoren -- tOrte -- tTexte -- tBilddenkmäler0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe rich corpus of literary otherworld journeys that has survived from the Scandinavian - and especially the Icelandic - Middle Ages is in many respects tied to a space 'Between the Worlds'. Every otherworld journey quite literally engages with a space 'between the worlds' in the sense that it plays itself out between this world and a world beyond, an otherworld. Yet this is not all. Also in terms of its cultural context this branch of the literature of the medieval North takes up a position situated midway between a broad range of poles. Texts from the Christian period treat pre-Christian mythology; allegedly pre-Christian material is studded with Christian motifs; Scandinavian texts adapt the learning and literature of the European continent, Ireland, and the classical Mediterranean; and Finnish narratives in turn appear to adapt Scandinavian narrative patterns. The volume presents a rich panorama of a broad range of very different - Scandinavian, Finno-Ugric, Greek, Latin, Celtic, Ancient Near Eastern, and archaeological - perspectives on the topic of the 'otherworld journey', which contextualises the motif of the otherworld journey in Old Norse-Icelandic literature in an unprecedented breadth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Scandinavian.2bisacsh  aAfterlife.  acomparison of religions.  amythology.  aotherworld.1 aEgeler, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgeler, Matthias, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrog,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardeła, Leszek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeizmann, Wilhelm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeizmann, Wilhelm, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHofeneder, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaul, Flemming, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathúna, Séamus Mac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMetcalf, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNesselrath, Heinz-Günther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorth, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOehrl, Sigmund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchjødt, Jens Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmalzer, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Horst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStarý, Jiří, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTeichert, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb